<poem>
<title poet="Spencer_A">The Wife-Woman</title>

<stanza>
    <l n="1"><figLang form="metaphor">Maker-of-Sevens in the schemeof thing</figLang>s</l>
<l n="2">to star<punc type="semicolon">;</punc></l>
<l n="3">Thy cycle holds whatever is fate, and</l>
<l n="4">Over the border the bar.</l>
<l n="5">Though rank and fierce<figLang form="metaphor">the mariner</figLang></l>
<l n="6">Sailing the seven seas<punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
<l n="7"><figLang form="metaphor">He prays as he holds his glass to his eyes</figLang></l>
<l n="8">Coaxing the Pleiades <punc type="period">.</punc></l>
</stanza>
    <stanza>
<l n="9">I cannot love them; and I feel your glad,</l>
<l n="10" >Chiding from the grave<punc type="comma">,</punc></l>
<l n="11">That my all was only worth at all<punc type="comma">,</punc> what</l>
<l n="12">Joy to you it gave,</l>
<l n="13"><figLang form="personification">These seven links the Law compelled</figLang></l>
<l n="14">For the human chain—</l>
<l n="15">I cannot love them<punc type="semicolon">;</punc> and you, oh,</l>
<l n="16">Seven-fold months in Flanders slain!</l>
    </stanza>

<stanza>
<l n="17">there<punc type="comma">, a cave here,</punc> bred six</l>
<l n="18">And a million years<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
<l n="19">Sure and strong, mate for mate, such</l>
<l n="20">Love as culture fears;</l>
<l n="21">I gave you clear the oil and wine<punc type="semicolon">;</punc></l>
<l n="22">You saved me your hob and hearth—</l>
<l n="23">See how even life may be ere the</l>
<l n="24">Sickle comes and leaves a swath<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
</stanza>
<stanza>
<l n="25">But I can wait the seven of moons,</l>
<l n="26">Or years I spare,</l>
<l n="27">it's plenty, nor spend</l>
<l n="28">A drop, nor share—</l>
<l n="29">So long but outlives a smile and</l>
<l n="30">A silken gown<punc type="semicolon">;</punc></l>
<l n="31">Then gaily I reach up from my shroud,</l>
<l n="32">And you, glory-clad, reach down<punc type="period">.</punc> </l>
</stanza>
</poem>